										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Perhaps the scariest part of the <a href="https://technet.microsoft.com/library/security/2963983" title="It goes alway the way back to IE 6.">recent remote execution vulnerability in Internet Explorer</a> is this thought from <a href="http://krebsonsecurity.com/2014/04/microsoft-warns-of-attacks-on-ie-zero-day/" title="Why isn't the 'Enhanced Mitigation Experience Toolkit' shipped with Windows?">Brian Krebs</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p>
This is the first of many zero-day attacks and vulnerabilities that will never be fixed for Windows XP users. Microsoft last month shipped its final set of updates for XP. Unfortunately, many of the exploit mitigation techniques that EMET brings do not work inÂ XP.
</p></blockquote>
<p>According to <a href="http://gs.statcounter.com/#os-US-monthly-201303-201403-bar" title="Their global stats site is super useful for this type of data.">StatCounter</a> Windows XP still accounts for 10% of systems browsing the web in the United States.  That includes mobile users too.</p>
<p><a href="/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/statcounter-os-march-2014-1.jpg" title="More than Android?"><img loading="lazy" src="/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/statcounter-os-march-2014-1.jpg" alt="statcounter-os-march-2014" width="845" height="540" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-10383" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/statcounter-os-march-2014-1.jpg 845w, /wp-content/uploads/2014/04/statcounter-os-march-2014-1-300x192.jpg 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2014/04/statcounter-os-march-2014-1-768x491.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 845px) 100vw, 845px" /></a></p>
<p>When you look at the <a href="http://gs.statcounter.com/#all-os-ww-monthly-201303-201403-bar" title="I wonder which country has the highest use of Windows XP in the world.">world wide use</a> that 10% jumps to 16%.</p>
<p>I expect there are people who are still actively looking for holes in Windows XP.  It is only a matter of time before they find them.</p>
